  "@type": "Article",
  "dateModified": "2026-03-06",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Coherence is the quality that makes a piece of writing feel unified and logically connected — the reader\u0026rsquo;s sense that ideas follow from one another and that the whole adds up to more than its parts. It is distinguished from cohesion, which is the local connection between sentences through linguistic devices (transitional words, repeated terms, pronouns). Cohesion is the glue; coherence is the architecture.\nA text can be cohesive without being coherent: every sentence can flow grammatically into the next while the overall argument goes nowhere. And a text can be coherent without heavy cohesion: a reader who understands the governing idea can follow sections that don\u0026rsquo;t use explicit transitions, because the logic connecting them is clear.\n",
